Day18:
Create an IAM policy named iampolicy_anita in us-east-1 region, it must allow read-only access to the EC2 console,
i.e this policy must allow users to view all instances, AMIs, and snapshots in the Amazon EC2 console.

Steps Using AWS Console:
1. Login to AWS Console:
Go to the AWS Management Console.
Log in with your credentials.
2. Navigate to IAM Service:
In the search bar at the top, type IAM and select IAM from the list of services.
3. Create a New IAM Policy:
In the left sidebar under Access management, click on Policies.
Click the Create policy button.
4. Define the Policy JSON:
Choose the JSON tab.
Copy and paste the following policy JSON, which allows read-only access to EC2 resources (instances, AMIs, and snapshots):
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "ec2:DescribeInstances",
        "ec2:DescribeImages",
        "ec2:DescribeSnapshots",
        "ec2:DescribeSecurityGroups",
        "ec2:DescribeKeyPairs",
        "ec2:DescribeVolumes",
        "ec2:DescribeVolumesModifications",
        "ec2:DescribeTags"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
This policy grants the user permission to:
View EC2 instances, AMIs, snapshots, volumes, security groups, and tags.
5. Review and Create the Policy:
Click Review policy.
Name the policy iampolicy_anita.
Add an optional description (e.g., "Read-only access to EC2 instances, AMIs, and snapshots").
Click Create policy to create the policy.

Steps Using AWS CLI:
1. Create the IAM Policy:
To create the IAM policy iampolicy_anita with read-only access to EC2, use the following AWS CLI command. Create a JSON file with the policy or directly use the JSON string.
Step 1: Create the policy JSON file (policy.json):
Create a file named policy.json with the following content:
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "ec2:DescribeInstances",
        "ec2:DescribeImages",
        "ec2:DescribeSnapshots",
        "ec2:DescribeSecurityGroups",
        "ec2:DescribeKeyPairs",
        "ec2:DescribeVolumes",
        "ec2:DescribeVolumesModifications",
        "ec2:DescribeTags"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
Step 2: Run the following AWS CLI command to create the policy:
aws iam create-policy --policy-name iampolicy_anita --policy-document file://policy.json --region us-east-1
Explanation:
--policy-name iampolicy_anita: The name of the IAM policy.
--policy-document file://policy.json: The path to the JSON file containing the policy definition.
--region us-east-1: The region (although IAM policies are global, this parameter specifies the region for CLI interactions).
2. Verify the Policy Creation:
You can verify the policy was created successfully by running:
aws iam get-policy --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/iampolicy_anita --region us-east-1
